name: Nancy Pelosi
content:
Today, Americans mark a solemn milestone: forty years since the discovery of HIV/AIDS, a disease that has inflicted nearly unparalleled anguish, pain and devastation on our country and world. On this day, we take time to mourn the hundreds of thousands of Americans we have lost to this vicious disease and pray for all grieving their tragic loss. We also pay tribute to the more than one million Americans living with HIV today, who have bravely battled not only the virus but its cruel stigma.

In San Francisco, we remember the darkest months of the start of the crisis, when many of us were visiting the hospital constantly and attending two funerals a day. Today, we are blessed to be able to celebrate the birthdays, weddings and retirements of our long-term survivors. Despite these achievements, our nation still loses 13,000 Americans every year to AIDS – a toll that breaks our hearts and continues to demand our urgent action.

As we celebrate the tremendous progress made to defeat this disease, we must recommit to finishing this fight. As Speaker, I have been proud to lead Congress’s response to HIV/AIDS, including securing billions for treatment, prevention, community-based models of care, and the search for a cure here at home and abroad, as well as providing affordable housing for low-income survivors through HOPWA and expanding access to quality, affordable health care for those affected. As we carry on the fight today, the Democratic Congress looks forward to working with the Biden-Harris Administration to fully fund initiatives to end this epidemic at home and abroad.

Today, and every day, let us renew our vow to always support our long-term survivors and work to finally banish HIV to the dustbin of history.

name: Jeff Merkley
content:
Obviously, I’m disappointed by Senator Manchin’s position. The For the People Act is popular among Democrats, Republicans, and independents all across the country.

It is popular because Americans love the vision of government of, by, and for the People, and that means ending the deep corruption that comes from gerrymandering, billionaires buying elections, and attacks on the freedom and right of every American to vote.

I wish with all my heart that this bill weren’t necessary, or that Republicans in the Senate would join us in defending Americans’ right to vote. But in the face of a coup attempt incited by a president trying to overturn an election and a nationwide attempt to ensure that the will of the voters does not determine the outcome of future elections, I am dead set against doing nothing.

As I have told all my colleagues many times, I am open to any conversation about the provisions of this bill, and will not give up on American democracy.

#ForThePeople

name: Adam B. Schiff
content:
This year has already been the worst on record for anti-LGBTQ+ bills. Republicans in state legislatures across the country are continuing their vitriolic campaign to dehumanize transgender individuals, especially children. They know exactly what they’re doing – they’re putting targets on the backs of vulnerable children to score cheap political points. And it’s shameful.

These ongoing attempts to curtail the basic human rights of transgender Americans are causing immense fear across California, and we must never stop fighting to ensure that equality – for all – remains the law of the land.

We will continue challenging these laws at every turn, in every possible venue. And we’ll work to pass federal non-discrimination standards, like the Equality Act, which will prevent discrimination in housing, healthcare, education, and so much more.

This Pride month, and every month, let’s all recommit to standing in absolute solidarity with the LGBTQ+ community – together, we’re stronger than hate.

name: Garret Graves
content:
Where are your drainage problems? We have been traveling around today and over the past several weeks talking with many of you about drainage and flooding problems. It is clear that there are problems all over south Louisiana. Some issues are related to leaves and litter getting into yards and streets -\-\ these block catch basins, ditches and canals (as seen in the pictures). In some cases, outfall pipes that were designed to drain our areas are too low in the canals -\-\ causing water to back-flow into our homes (as seen in the pictures). In other cases, it is canals, ditches, bayous and rivers that have not been properly maintained -\-\ filled with debris, trees, litter and sediment. We have secured a record $3,000,000,000 for the state and parishes to help address many of our flood/drainage problems. I'm not sure the funds are being put in the right places or executed with the urgency you deserve. The state has only spent a fraction of the $1.2 billion under a program we provided years ago -\-\ and almost none of this has been spent on actually fixing problems.
In an effort to help us identify the flooding and drainage problems for state officials managing these funds and some of the parishes working on this, post your pictures and the location of where water backs up.

name: Alan S. Lowenthal
content:
I have been championing the protection of our environment since before I came to Congress. I applaud the Biden Administration actions announced today that will reverse policies implemented under President Donald Trump that weakened the Endangered Species Act (ESA). The nearly 50-year-old ESA is one of our most significant conservation and environmental protection laws and since enacted in 1973 has been credited with the recovery of dozens of threatened species, including the bald eagle, humpback whale, grizzly bear, and the gray wolf. The ESA is still considered one of the world's strongest species protection laws and we must continue to enforce, protect, and strengthen it--both for our environment today, but also for the environment of tomorrow.

name: Sam Graves
content:
On the morning of June 6, 1944, American, British, and allied troops stormed the beaches of Normandy, France.

They were met a hail of machine gun and artillery fire while trying to swim, crawl, run, and fight to survive.

They failed to capture many of their major objectives that day, including Carentan, St. Lo, and Bayeux. But, they succeeded in their most important mission—to gain a foothold for freedom in Nazi-occupied Europe.

name: Richard J. Durbin
content:
Earlier this week, I had the honor of joining Lori Lightfoot, Mike Quigley, Alderman Harry Osterman, and Alderman James Cappleman for the groundbreaking of the next section of the CTA Red and Purple Modernization (RPM) Project.

It’s been nearly a decade since I helped create the Core Capacity program to assist transit systems like the CTA in making necessary upgrades to aging infrastructure like the Red and Purple lines, which were built nearly a century ago. In the time since, I have helped secure more than $1 billion in federal funding for the RPM project. I will continue working with the Chicago members of the Congressional Delegation to bring home federal investments to make sure that the CTA can continue serving the people of Chicago for the next 100 years.

I introduced the Lowering Medicare Premiums and Prescription Drug Costs Act because no one should have to choose between their health care and other basic needs. This bill reimagines programs that provide financial assistance to low-income seniors and people with disabilities.

The Lowering Medicare Premiums and Prescription Drug Costs Act would expand access to programs that help seniors and people with disabilities shoulder the cost of premiums and cost-sharing for Medicare. This bill reimagines programs that provide financial assistance to cover the costs of Medicare, making them more generous and eliminating barriers that prevented eligible seniors and people with disabilities from accessing much-needed assistance.

name: John Boozman
content:
Yesterday the U.S. Air Force announced Ebbing Air National Guard Base in Fort Smith has been selected as the home of future F-35 fighter planes and a Republic of Singapore F-16 squadron.

This decision strengthens Arkansas’s role in our nation’s defense. I’m proud the Air Force and the Republic of Singapore recognized what we’ve known all along – Fort Smith is the ideal location for this mission. This is a win for the community and the entire state that was made possible in part thanks to the dedicated citizens who have tirelessly advocated the opportunities that exist here.

For the past year, I’ve worked alongside Governor Asa Hutchinson, Senator Tom Cotton and Rep. Steve Womack, in collaboration with state and community leaders, to promote the unique capabilities and assets the Fort Smith region offers for military training and readiness. We also urged the Federal Aviation Administration to expand military airspace in order to provide more opportunities for specialized training.

This has been a team effort from top to bottom and, as a proud son of Fort Smith, I’m excited we have made it to this point because of what this decision will mean for the city, the region and our state.

name: Bill Johnson
content:
Today is the 77th anniversary of the D-Day landing…and, it’s befitting that we all stop and think for a moment about how God’s hand of divine providence ensured the success of that critical mission.

On June 6, 1944, some 175,000 allied and American troops waited to storm the beaches of Normandy, France to rid Europe of Nazi terror…among those were 57,000 Americans. I was at Normandy two years ago, and I overheard a veteran tell this story. He said, and I paraphrase…

When they were awakened that morning on June 6, it was pretty quiet on board the ships. They were busy getting their gear and weapons ready to go so that when it was their turn to get into the beach landing craft, they’d be ready. No one was talking, every man was deep in his thoughts. Then a superior came in and gave the mission orders…the pep talk. He said, “Men, your mission is to…take out two targets before you’re killed.”

Imagine hearing that, “take out two targets before you’re killed!” That had to have been a very sobering pep talk. I can’t imagine what my reaction would have been upon hearing those words, but I hope it would have been the same reaction those men had. You see, in spite of knowing that there was a strong likelihood that many of them would be killed instantly, they all still got onto the beach landing craft.

I believe God showed up in the hearts and minds of those brave men that day…and, I suspect he reminded them of that emotional passage in the Bible. Because each and every one of those men, both those who died and those who miraculously survived, put everything on the line for not only their friends and families…but, for millions of people they did not even know.

John 15:13 – “Greater love hath no man than this, that a man lay down his life for his friends.”

I’m grateful that God still touches the hearts of America’s young people and convinces them to put on the American military uniform and march off into harm’s way to protect and defend my freedom. Thank you to all those who served and are still serving today. God bless the United States of America.

name: Bill Huizenga
content:
There has been an ongoing discussion about Washington creating disincentives for individuals returning to work. A recent study by economists Casey Mulligan, E.J. Antoni and Steve Moore estimates that in “21 states households that qualify can receive a maximum wage equivalent of $25 an hour in cash without working. In 19 states, the maximum benefit is the equivalent of $100,000 a year in salary for a family of four with two unemployed parents,” according to the Wall Street Journal. With labor shortages across nearly all sectors, Michigan should join the number of states ending the $300 unemployment kicker. Small businesses can’t compete with the federal government putting it’s thumb on the scale.

name: Bill Johnson
content:
Today marks 77 years since the D-Day invasion, the final push to free the world from Nazi tyranny. America, along with our allies, sent our most prized possession - our youth - onto French shores to defeat fascism and liberate a continent.

We’re making progress on getting the permanent plaque with the prayer President Franklin Roosevelt prayed with the nation on June 6, 1944. The World War II Memorial Prayer Act, that I authored along with Senator Portman, directs the Secretary of the Interior to install a plaque near the WWII Memorial with President Roosevelt’s words of the D-Day Prayer, “Let Our Hearts Be Stout.” Private funding has been secured, and the planning is almost complete. It's been a long process - the legislation was signed into law in 2014 - but we are nearing the finish line. FDR's powerful message should be seen by future generations that visit the memorial – and thanks to our legislation, it soon will be.

name: Thomas R. Suozzi
content:
Seventy-seven years ago today, on June 6, 1944, 156,000 American, British and Canadian forces landed on five beaches along a 50-mile stretch of the heavily fortified coast of Normandy, France. The invasion was one of the largest amphibious military assaults in history and proved to be a critical turning point in World War II. More than 4,000 Allied soldiers, sailors, airmen, and coastguardsmen perished on the 24-hour period known as D-Day.

Two years ago, I participated in a bipartisan Congressional Delegation to commemorate the 75th Anniversary of D-Day. The experience was truly sobering and humbling. Seventy-seven years later, the sacrifice made on the beaches of Normandy must be remembered and revered. These brave souls demand that we earn the sacrifice they made by lifting up our freedom and our democracy and participating in our politics and government in a way that is nobler.

May we never forget the service and sacrifice of our "Greatest Generation."

name: Tammy Baldwin
content:
I’m at Outreach Community Health Center with parents and local leaders discussing the need to reverse the trend of rising maternal mortality rates, close health disparities that put Black, Indigenous, and People of Color (BIPOC) communities and their kids at greater risk of adverse health outcomes, and improve maternal health outcomes in Wisconsin.

We know that there are racial health care disparities we must address. We know that maternal and infant mortality rates are high in Wisconsin. And we know that they are even tragically higher in Wisconsin’s Black community.

In February, I introduced the Perinatal Workforce Act with Congresswoman Gwen Moore to improve access to maternity care, and grow and diversify the perinatal health workforce. And last month, I joined Senator Cory Booker, Gwen, and others to introduce the MOMMIES Act to extend Medicaid coverage for pregnant and postpartum women.

I believe we need to comprehensively address every dimension of the Black maternal health crisis. We need to do more to provide every woman in America the maternal health care she needs to have a safe and healthy pregnancy.

name: Brian Babin
content:
In 2019, I traveled to France on a Congressional Delegation trip to pay tribute to the 75th anniversary of D-Day. Today, on the 77th anniversary, I’m remembering back on that most solemn experience. I’ll never forget meeting with numerous veterans of D-Day, walking along the beaches of Normandy, peering inside German pillboxes, or visiting the graves of the nearly 10,000 soldiers who paid the ultimate price defending our liberty on June 6, 1944. It was an absolute honor to tread on such hallowed ground where so many heroes fell.

I remain incredibly proud to be an American, and am extremely grateful to those who have fought and died to ensure that our country, and its people, remain free.

name: Bill Johnson
content: Lancaster, Ohio native General William Sherman is this week’s famous Ohioan. His military career began at West Point at age 16, where he rose through the ranks, eventually replacing Ulysses S. Grant as the Union Commander during the Civil War. A few years later, he was made the Commanding General of the Army, a post he held for over 10 years under four presidents. His aggressive military strategies have been studied throughout the years, and inspired many famous military minds, including General George S. Patton. He played pivotal roles in holding America together during the Civil War and rebuilding America during post-Civil War reconstruction.

name: Lisa Murkowski
content:
According to reports, several tons of genetically engineered salmon will soon make its way to restaurants. I’ve long held the belief that it is absolutely essential that consumers be fully informed about what they are buying and feeding their families—especially when it comes to purchasing a genetically engineered salmon product. I reintroduced the Genetically Engineered Salmon Labeling Act, which will allow consumers to make informed decisions when purchasing salmon. The bill works to ensure that any genetically engineered salmon products sold in the U.S. are clearly labeled “genetically engineered” in the market name. As an Alaskan who knows the tremendous benefits of eating healthy, wild Alaskan salmon, it’s imperative that Americans have the information to make that choice.

MURKOWSKI.SENATE.GOV
Murkowski and Colleagues Stand Up for Wild-Caught Salmon | U.S. Senator Lisa Murkowski of Alaska

name: Austin Scott
content:
Seventy-seven years ago, Allied troops stormed the beaches at Normandy in a fight to free Europe from tyranny and oppression. They were met with fierce bombardment, and thousands perished in the water, skies, and on the beaches that day in what is still the largest seaborne invasion in history.

The determination and bravery of the Allied forces that day laid the foundation for the liberation of Europe and the surrender of Nazi Germany in May 1945. Today, we remember and give thanks to our many service members who bravely fought and paid the ultimate sacrifice at Normandy to protect freedom with one goal in mind: "nothing less than full victory.”

“You are about to embark upon the Great Crusade, toward which we have striven these many months. The eyes of the world are upon you. The hopes and prayers of liberty-loving people everywhere march with you." - Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower

name: Lee M. Zeldin
content:
The VA estimates that nearly 20 veterans take their own lives each day in the US, oftentimes due to the invisible wounds known as Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder. This PTSD Awareness Month, it's important to honor and remember all those who have lost their lives to this terrible affliction, but we must also work to spread the word about treatment options for those suffering from PTSD. The PFC Joseph P. Dwyer Veteran Peer Support Program, which I created while serving in the New York State Senate, helps veterans overcome PTSD and successfully transition to post-service life by creating a safe, confidential and educational network for veterans to support each other and share common experiences. I'm so grateful for the many amazing veterans advocates across New York who have helped save countless veteran lives due to their efforts to make the Dwyer Program a huge success in our state. READ ⬇️ my op-ed in the Village Beacon Record about my efforts to expand the Dwyer Program nationally and make its critical services available to veterans across the country and help them overcome the mental wounds of war and return to civilian life.

https://zeldin.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/time-take-dwyer-program-national

name: Lisa Murkowski
content: In 2013, a bill I championed was signed into law that renamed the Talkeetna Ranger Station after the first man to summit Denali—Athabascan, Walter Harper. This week I checked in with the National Park Service employees at the Walter Harper Talkeetna Ranger Station to see how things are going. As the center of mountaineering operations for Denali National Park and Preserve, they not only help climbers with orientation and climbing permits before they begin their ascent, but also with emergency rescues for those who are injured or in danger throughout their climb. When we visited, there were a little over 500 folks climbing the mountain. This is lower than previous seasons, but still a lot of lives to help oversee. I appreciate all our Park Rangers are doing to help ensure visitors have the safest, most enjoyable Alaskan experience possible.

name: Steve Chabot
content: 77 years ago today, the D-Day invasion began, as more than 150,000 Allied troops stormed the beaches of Normandy. It's difficult to overstate just how critical the Normandy invasion was not only to our success in World War II, but also to the future of democracy and freedom around the globe. As President Franklin D. Roosevelt said of the Allied soldiers when announcing the invasion to the American people: "They fight not for the lust of conquest. They fight to end conquest. They fight to liberate." And liberate they did. A little less than a year later, Nazi Germany was defeated, and the War in Europe was over. We owe a tremendous amount of gratitude to the men and women of the greatest generation for the sacrifices they made, both at home and abroad, to keep us free and protect us from tyranny. God bless each of you, and God bless America!

name: J. Hill
content:
Today, 77 years ago, the Allied Forces forces of the United States, Britian, Canada, and France gained a victory over Axis powers marking the turning point in World War II.

Then-General Dwight D. Eisenhower, Supreme Allied Commander, encouraged his troops on June 6, 1944, saying, "Your task will not be an easy one. Your enemy is well-trained, well equipped and battle-hardened. He will fight savagely…. I have full confidence in your courage, devotion to duty and skill in battle. We will accept nothing less than full Victory!"

General Eisenhower's confidence in his troops, as well as the wherewithal of Allied troops, helped protect the freedoms we enjoy today at home and across the entire continent of Europe. Allied forces went on to accept Germany’s unconditional surrender not twelve months later on May 8, 1845.

name: Brian Babin
content:
Seventy-seven years ago, the “Day of Days” commenced as the U.S. launched the largest amphibious invasion in the history of warfare, preceded by an airborne assault, along the beaches of Normandy, France. As Operation Neptune unfolded, thousands of American and Allied troops courageously took to the beaches to fight – willing to sacrifice all – for freedom. Only those who experienced it can truly fathom the bravery displayed by so many on D-Day as Allied forces victoriously took Normandy and turned the tide of the war. Eventually, this led to the liberation of Europe and the defeat of Nazi Germany.

Today, join me in remembering and thanking the heroes who stormed the beaches, piloted the planes, parachuted behind enemy lines, operated the thousands of ships, and fought valiantly to preserve the freedoms we cherish every single day. The weight of this sacrifice is as heavy today as it was in 1944. While the liberation of Europe came at a high price, it is a price America has always been willing to pay in the protection of freedom.

“The eyes of the world are upon you. The hopes and prayers of liberty-loving people everywhere march with you.” – General Dwight D. Eisenhower, 1944

name: Dan Sullivan
content:
Over twenty-five years ago, I was deployed as part of a U.S. Marine Corps amphibious task force to the Taiwan Strait during a very challenging and critical time for Taiwan’s democracy. America’s presence then was in response to Chinese provocations on the eve of the presidential election in Taiwan and it demonstrated American commitment and resolve.

This morning, I led a bipartisan Senate delegation visit to Taiwan in yet another demonstration of that continued commitment to our friends and partners in this critical area of the world, as well as a reminder of how the United States’ presence over the past several decades has been instrumental in the development of security, prosperity and democracy throughout the Indo-Pacific region. It is also a demonstration that, in spite of a global pandemic emanating from China—characterized by a lack of transparency and lack of international cooperation from the Chinese Communist Party—the United States, by contrast, is committed to working in a constructive and open manner with our friends, allies and partners to bring healing and relief with effective vaccines that benefit our own citizens, as well as others throughout the world. I want to thank my colleagues, Senators Duckworth and Coons, as well as the elected leaders and citizens of Taiwan, for their continued commitment to the advancement of security, democracy and health and prosperity throughout the Indo-Pacific region.

SULLIVAN.SENATE.GOV
Sens. Sullivan, Duckworth & Coons Visit Taipei to Underscore U.S. Support for Taiwan, Announce Allocation of 750,000 Vaccine Doses to Taiwan | U.S. Senator Dan Sullivan of Alaska

name: Susan M. Collins
content:
It is difficult to imagine the Maine press corps without its dean, Mal Leary. He covered the news with a knowledge of the history of the issues and the participants that was unparalleled. His questions were tough but always fair. Mal’s stories were accurate, balanced, and informative. Mal will be greatly missed.

Mal Leary
June 5 at 9:16 AM ·

Folks-
After 45 years of reporting, I am retiring July 2, 2021.

It has been quite a ride helping to write the first draft of Maine history for over 40 years. I covered the first independent Governor, and the first woman Governor and literally thousands of people through the years.

TV News, documentaries, radio news both commercial and public and writing for every daily newspaper in the state has been a rewarding career.
Looking back, I have written about every major issue to face the state and sometimes I got it right.

Truth telling generates both friends and enemies, and I have had my share of both. But I wouldn’t do it differently.

Mal

name: Dan Sullivan
content:
Living in a small, highly-rural community far from a major metropolitan center does not justify a veteran losing or receiving limited access to the health care they have earned and sacrificed for. Community-centered approaches to health care delivery, coupled with advancements in technology and tele-health, can enable the VA to better deliver care to veterans wherever they live, especially those who find themselves in the "gaps" without service—like in Alaska’s many remote towns and villages. I introduced legislation with some of my Veterans Affairs Committee colleagues and Chairman Jerry Moran to seize this opportunity and fulfill our responsibility to the men and women who have bravely served our country.

SULLIVAN.SENATE.GOV
Sullivan, Colleagues Introduce Legislation to Address Gaps in Veteran Health Care | U.S. Senator Dan Sullivan of Alaska

Altoona-Midway USD 387
June 3 at 3:38 PM ·

We would like to sincerely thank the many of you who have reached out with offers of donations/supplies following the fire at the elementary building. We asked the teachers to put together a wish list of items to make it easier for those who would like to donate, so we will be posting several links to wish lists in the days to come. *Please note that when shared, only the link to the wish list will be shared, and not our original post.* Thank you all for the support!

name: Lisa Murkowski
content: In Fairbanks, I visited with the staff of the Interior Alaska Center for Non-Violent Living. We covered a number of topics, including the challenges of providing services in light of the COVID-19 pandemic – including the challenge of getting victims to come into the clinic during the pandemic, capacity issues, and regulations around feeding those who receive services at the clinic. We also talked about their concern over VOCA cuts—funding which pays for their personnel and staff, allowing them to provide services to those in need. Our visit was a reminder of how important it is that the Senate passes the VOCA Fix to Sustain the Crime Victims Fund Act – a bill I’m pushing to help protect vital victim service programs by preventing future cuts to already diminished federal grants.

name: James P. McGovern
content:
Yesterday at The Food Bank of Western Mass. I was thrilled to welcome Joel Berg of Hunger Free America as part of a national tour to help re-focus attention on America’s hunger crisis.

Throughout the pandemic, Joel and I have shared a common goal of raising awareness of the fact that food insecurity in the United States remains critically high and we’ve stressed the need to provide the American people with long-term solutions.

We visited The Food Bank farm in Hadley, which provides an innovative approach to addressing food insecurity in Western Massachusetts.

The local impact of the work being done in Hadley should be highlighted and modeled on a national level. And I plan to do just that.

Since the beginning of the 117th Congress, as Chairman of the Rules Committee, I’ve begun a series of nationwide anti-hunger hearings, roundtables, meetings, press conferences, and visits to uplift a diverse chorus of voices, so that when the Biden administration is ready to hold a hunger conference, they can hit the ground running with ideas and feedback readily available to help shape the dialogue.

While I appreciate Joel’s visit and attention to the Food Bank’s work, in a perfect world, his job wouldn’t even exist because there there’s simply no excuse for hunger is the wealthiest nation in world history.

This farm is the kind of program that we want to uplift as a path towards a hunger free America!

WWLP.COM
Food Bank of Western Massachusetts raising food insecurity awareness

name: James M. Inhofe
content:
Why do the Democrats still want to ratify the ERA? The National Organization for Women (NOW) revealed its true goal when it announced: “an ERA – properly interpreted – could negate the hundreds of laws that have been passed restricting access to abortion care and contraception.”

NARAL wrote in a national alert that, “With its ratification, the ERA would reinforce the constitutional right to abortion by clarifying that the sexes have equal rights, which would require judges to strike down anti-abortion laws…”

What they're really saying is enacting the ERA as a constitutional amendment would kill the numerous pro-life policies that continue to give a voice to the voiceless and protect the millions of unborn children—including women, the very population this amendment purports to protect.

Join me in honoring Dennis Richter for 50 years of perfect attendance at the Taylor Rotary Club. His dedication to service and his community is inspiring! Congratulations, Dennis! #TX31

Tia Rae Cody Stone‎Rotary Club of Taylor, TX
June 4 at 2:49 PM ·

The Rotary Club of Taylor and Congressman John Carter’s office recognized Dennis Richter for 50 years of perfect attendance at the Rotary Club of Taylor’s meeting on June 3. Julie Sharifian, Constituent Representative with Carter’s District TX-31 office, presented Dennis with a flag that flew over the United States Capitol Building on May 10, 2021, the date of the local club’s 100th anniversary. A Paul Harris Fellow, Dennis joined the club in 1971, served as president in 1974-75 and 1984-85 and was chosen Outstanding Citizen of the Year in 1989. He currently serves as the club’s sergeant-at-arms contributing tidbits of Rotary knowledge at every meeting. #1DistrictStrong #taylorrotary

name: John Boozman
content:
In 2019, I had the honor of joining a group of senators and congressman to Europe for the 75th anniversary of D-Day. Every moment was a reminder of the tragedy and triumph of that day, and the entire war. These Americans and our Allied partners faced a grueling, momentous challenge which they met and overcame to the tremendous pride and relief of so many. We are forever grateful for what they did and gave here to turn the tide of a war, uphold the promise of freedom and defeat the forces of tyranny. These heroes truly changed the world.

Today, as we reflect on D-Day 77 years later, here are some of my reflections from the D-Day 75th Anniversary commemoration in Normandy (June 6, 2019).

name: Doug Lamborn
content:
June 6th 2021 marks the 77th anniversary of D-Day and the Battle of Normandy.

Today we remember and honor the brave and we commemorate our heroes who came from far and wide to restore freedom to Europe and across the world.

The National WWII Museum posted a video to playlist Voices of The Greatest Generation.
June 6, 2016 at 7:25 AM ·

To all who landed on Omaha Beach on June 6, 1944, it will be remembered as "Bloody Omaha" to them.

#OnThisDay in 1944, the Allies suffered approximately 12,000 casualties. The men that survived this bloody first 24 hours on the beaches of Normandy would embark upon a campaign to liberate northern France and drive towards Paris. But victory over Nazism was a far distant goal as the day ended on June 6, 1944. Berlin remained nearly 700 miles distant from Normandy. Much hard fighting remained for the Allied forces.

Visitors to the Museum can follow in the footsteps of these American troops as they make their way into Germany in our exhibit Road to Berlin: http://bit.ly/1SLGsrZ #DDay72 #DDay

name: J. Hill
content:
It was an honor today to host my annual Service Academy Send Off, which honored 4 cadets and midshipmen that will be a part of the class of 2025 at our service academies. I was also able to congratulate 2LT Adam Hoxeng, who I nominated to West Point 4 years ago and has just graduated.

All of these exemplary students are the best of central Arkansas and our nation. I thank them for their future service and look forward to following their success.

Put together your emergency supply kit long before a wildfire or other disaster occurs and keep it easily accessible so you can take it with you when you have to evacuate. Plan to be away from your home for an extended period of time. Each person should have a readily accessible emergency supply kit...
